default4. Continuing fitness to practisedefault4.1
default              
defaultThis section outlines 
defaultour rationale
default and on-going work in the area of continuing fitness to practise. We use this term 
default(
defaultin line with the approach taken in the PSA’s 2013 report 
defaulton this topic
default)
default to describe the steps taken by regulators (and others) to support fitness to practise beyond the point of initial registration. 
defaultThis term 
defaultreflects our
default outcomes-focus
defaulted
default approach
default and avoids ‘revalidation’ which is often poorly defined.
default4.2
default              
defaultSin
defaultce 2003
default, 
defaultwe have required
default registrants to renew their registration every two years. Since 2006, 
defaultregistrants have had a compulsory, statutory requirement to undertake continuing professional development
default (CPD)
default.
default 
defaultOur
default standards for CPD 
defaultare focused
default on outcomes – the benefits of CPD to services users and quality of care.
default These standards are 
defaultlinked to registration and 
defaultare
default 
defaultunderpinned by random audits. We consider that auditing is a proportionate method of ensuring 
defaultcompliance
default. We 
defaultcan and do
default remove indi
defaultviduals from the Register where our standards have not been met. We 
defaultalso have
default in place requirements for those seeking to return to the Register after a period out of practice. 
